  "text": "Mitochondrial superoxide production during IR injury IR injury occurs when the blood supply to a tissue is blocked for minutes to hours (ischaemia), and then restored (reperfusion). There has long been an interest in better understanding IR injury and in developing therapies to prevent its damaging effects. Ischaemic cells will die if blood flow is not restored, but it is during reperfusion itself that most IR damage is initiated. The first damaging event upon reperfusion is a burst of ROS production from mitochondria that initiates the pathology that develops over the minutes, days and weeks following reperfusion [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The initial burst of ROS production upon reperfusion directly causes oxidative damage to mitochondria, and in conjunction with dysregulation of calcium levels, this elevated ROS can also lead to induction of the mitochondrial permeability transition and on to cell death following reperfusion [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
